{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Attributes","slug":"html-attributes","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"15 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Elements"],"learning_objectives":["Understand the purpose of attributes","Learn the syntax of name=\"value\"","Learn common attributes like href, src, width, height, alt, style, lang, title"],"theory":"# What are Attributes?\n\nAttributes provide **additional information** about HTML elements.\n\n*   All HTML elements can have attributes.\n*   Attributes are always specified in the **start tag**.\n*   Attributes usually come in name/value pairs like: `name=\"value\"`.\n\n## Common Attributes\n\n### 1. `href` Attribute\nUsed in `<a>` tags to specify the URL of the page the link goes to.\n```html\n<a href=\"https://www.google.com\">Visit Google</a>\n```\n\n### 2. `src` Attribute\nUsed in `<img>` tags to specify the path to the image to be displayed.\n```html\n<img src=\"image.jpg\">\n```\n\n### 3. `width` and `height` Attributes\nSpecify the size of images (in pixels).\n```html\n<img src=\"img.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"600\">\n```\n\n### 4. `alt` Attribute\nSpecifies an alternative text for an image if the image cannot be displayed (crucial for accessibility).\n```html\n<img src=\"img.jpg\" alt=\"A cute cat\">\n```\n\n### 5. `style` Attribute\nUsed to add styles to an element, such as color, font, size, etc.\n```html\n<p style=\"color:red;\">This is red text.</p>\n```\n\n### 6. `lang` Attribute\nUsed in the `<html>` tag to declare the language of the webpage.\n```html\n<html lang=\"en\">\n```\n\n### 7. `title` Attribute\nDefines some extra information about an element. usually shown as a **tooltip** when the mouse moves over the element.\n```html\n<p title=\"I am a tooltip\">Hover over me!</p>\n```\n\n## Quoting Attribute Values\nTypically, we use **double quotes**. Single quotes can also be used, but double quotes are the standard convention.","syntax":"<tagname attribute=\"value\">Content</tagname>","examples":[{"code":"<a href=\"https://example.com\">Link</a>\n<img src=\"logo.png\" alt=\"Logo\" width=\"100\">\n<p title=\"Info\">Hover me</p>","output":"Link (clickable), Logo image (100px wide), Text with tooltip.","explanation":"Attributes modify the behavior or presentation of the element."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Missing quotes around values","correction":"Always wrap values in quotes.","example":"❌ <a href=https://google.com>Link</a>\n✅ <a href=\"https://google.com\">Link</a>"},{"mistake":"Using space in attribute name","correction":"Attribute names do not have spaces.","example":"❌ <img start source=\"...\">\n✅ <img src=\"...\">"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Where do you define attributes?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Attributes are always defined in the opening (start) tag of an element."},{"question":"What is the importance of the alt attribute?","difficulty":"Intermediate","answer":"The alt attribute provides alternative text for screen readers (accessibility) and displays text if the image fails to load. It is crucial for SEO and users with visual impairments."},{"question":"Can I use single quotes for attributes?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Yes, single quotes are valid, but double quotes are the standard convention. Single quotes are useful if the attribute value itself contains a double quote."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Beginner","problem":"Create a link to 'https://openai.com' with the text 'Visit OpenAI' and a tooltip that says 'Go to AI site'.","hint":"Use <a> tag with href and title attributes.","solution":"<a href=\"https://openai.com\" title=\"Go to AI site\">Visit OpenAI</a>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Accessibility","description":"Screen readers rely heavily on attributes like 'alt' and 'lang' to interpret content for blind users.","code":"<html lang=\"en\"> ... <img alt=\"Description\">"}],"exam_notes":["Attributes = Name/Value pairs","Always in Start Tag","Quotes are mandatory for good practice","Key attributes: href (links), src (images), alt (image text), style (css), title (tooltip)"],"summary":"Attributes provide additional power and configuration to HTML elements. They allow you to define image sources, link destinations, stylistic choices, and accessible descriptions. Mastering attributes is key to making HTML elements functional.","order":6},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"content/html/html-editors.json","title":"HTML Editors & Tools","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"html-elements","path":"content/html/html-elements.json","title":"HTML Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"html-attributes","path":"content/html/html-attributes.json","title":"HTML Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":6},{"slug":"html-audio-video","path":"content/html/html-audio-video.json","title":"HTML Audio and Video","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":7},{"slug":"html-block-inline","path":"content/html/html-block-inline.json","title":"HTML Block and Inline Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":8},{"slug":"html-canvas","path":"content/html/html-canvas.json","title":"HTML Canvas","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":9},{"slug":"html-data-attributes","path":"content/html/html-data-attributes.json","title":"HTML Data Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":10},{"slug":"html-debugging"